<br>
1 in every 4 Americans lives near a Superfund site?  That's possible.  Do you realize how trivial most Superfund sites are?  We aren't talking about big holes full of nuclear waste.<br>
<br>
The Superfund is not the way that most toxic waste spills, etc. get cleaned up.  There is a federal statute called CERCLA that is used to make the polluter and other responsible parties pay for the clean up.  The Superfund is a fairly small part of the cleanup process.  It is used when someone else cannot be compelled to pay for the cleanup (for example, because the polluter went bankrupt or disappeared), and the cleanup must be performed by the government.<br>
<br>
The Democrats are pessimistic about stopping this.  Hmm.  The Democrats control the Senate at the moment.  That must mean that this has *gasp* bipartisan support.<br>
<br>
Frankly, the article doesn't contain enough information to allow anyone to make an informed judgment about what Bush is proposing.  Whoever wrote the article for Time is certainly against it, but only fools let the media do their thinking for them. <p>Sagemon Prayeth<BR>
